    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2135742719" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2135742719" />
    <a title="Elena Santangelo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5156475-elena-santangelo"><img alt="Elena Santangelo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1300714035p2/5156475.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2135742719?book_show_action=true">Oct 06, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elena Santangelo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elena Santangelo" href="/user/show/5156475-elena-santangelo">Elena Santangelo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5156475-elena-santangelo?shelf=short-stories">short-stories</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2135742719" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4571901061753819130">First, I don&apos;t know who wrote the summary and title for this book on Goodreads, but it certainly should NOT be labeled Hercule Poirot #41 as if it were a novel or collection of all Poirot shorts. Only 2 of the stories feature Poirot and they are the only 2 that can be called detective stories. The summary calls these &quot;previously unpublished&quot; stories. They were not only all previously published, but the notes at the end of each story lists the original publication. Many were also previously publi</span>
  <span id="freeText4571901061753819130" style="display:none">First, I don't know who wrote the summary and title for this book on Goodreads, but it certainly should NOT be labeled Hercule Poirot #41 as if it were a novel or collection of all Poirot shorts. Only 2 of the stories feature Poirot and they are the only 2 that can be called detective stories. The summary calls these "previously unpublished" stories. They were not only all previously published, but the notes at the end of each story lists the original publication. Many were also previously published in either the Hound of Death anthology (1933) or The Harlequin Tea Set (1989). I had read all these Christie stories before, though not in this collection.<br /><br />What this book IS is an anthology of Agatha Christie's earliest short stories, first published mostly in the 1920s, though some were written as early in her teenage years. It's an amazing look into the imagination of the author when she was first taking up the pen. Her craft wasn't polished, her style hadn't yet settled down to what we expect of Christie, but her talent and creativity hinted at what was to come.<br /><br />The majority of the stories aren't mysteries. They have been called romances, but only one, The Lonely God, would fit most people's definition of the word (though I have to admit, Lonely God is one of my absolute favorites in this collection). Instead, many of the stories are about complex relationships ~ psychological studies that you wouldn't expect from so young a writer, and beautifully written.<br /><br />The only disappointment is that some of the notes following the stories contain wrong information or information written so as to be misleading.<br /><br />It was wonderful to revisit these stories once more. I highly recommend this collection, not only for pure reading enjoyment, but for aspiring writers to study.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4571901061753819130" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


