    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_442359205" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/442359205" />
    <a title="Abbey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4437424-abbey"><img alt="Abbey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1287504365p2/4437424.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/442359205?book_show_action=true">Oct 26, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Abbey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Abbey" href="/user/show/4437424-abbey">Abbey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4437424-abbey?shelf=vintage">vintage</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4437424-abbey?shelf=myst-set-andor-auth-uk">myst-set-andor-auth-uk</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4437424-abbey?shelf=myst-fems-project">myst-fems-project</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4437424-abbey?shelf=short-stories">short-stories</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer442359205" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7124548830851757353"><b>[NOTE: despite title/description, this is NOT a Poirot novel, it&apos;s a collection of early Christie stories, only two of which are Poirot stories, one short story, one a novella; the remainder are not truly mysteries, they&apos;re sweet-but-spooky short stories]</b><br/><br/>WHILE THE LIGHT LASTS and other Stories, Agatha Christie<br/>1997, Nine creepy/supernatural stories, all initially published in magazines in the 1920s and 1930s; This collection was only published in the UK but all the other stories except one were p</span>
  <span id="freeText7124548830851757353" style="display:none"><b>[NOTE: despite title/description, this is NOT a Poirot novel, it's a collection of early Christie stories, only two of which are Poirot stories, one short story, one a novella; the remainder are not truly mysteries, they're sweet-but-spooky short stories]</b><br /><br />WHILE THE LIGHT LASTS and other Stories, Agatha Christie<br />1997, Nine creepy/supernatural stories, all initially published in magazines in the 1920s and 1930s; This collection was only published in the UK but all the other stories except one were published - also in 1997 but in the US only - under the title THE HARLEQUIN TEA SET and other Stories. The one difference between the two books is that the titular story The Harlequin Tea Set is only in the US version; the story Christmas Adventure is only in the UK volume. <br /><br />This is the sort of early 20th century short story collection (even though published in 1997) that has mainly very sentimental stories in it, albeit with nice Christie touches. And while some of the plots are rather good, the pacing tends to be very slow, with most of the writing being scene-setting, description and exposition, not action. <br /><br />WHILE THE LIGHT LASTS includes:<br />[dates = when story first published]<br /><br />1923 05	The Actress apa A Trap for the Unwary <br />		— a famous actress gets blackmailed and figures out quite an <br />			artistic way of removing the blackmailer<br /><br />1923 12	Christmas Adventure <br />		— terrifically twisted plot set in a classic English Manor House at<br />			Christmas, one of my favorite Christie stories, and one of my<br />			favorite Suchet/Poirot films as well. <br />[NOTE: The story printed in this collection was published again after its first magazine publication (1923) around 1960, with the alternate title(s) of Adventure of the Christmas Pudding or Theft of the Royal Ruby. The length was expanded from story length into novella length and the story rewritten rather a lot and set ~1950s, not its original 1920s. While the plot of both is similar, the characters are different in each version and the overall atmosphere is quite different (the revised 1960 version has references to TVs and LP records and has darkish edges, the 1923 version is much sweeter in tone). The original 1923 short story version is only available in this collection. The excellent film mainly uses the later, longer version but is as sentimental as the earlier version, sweetening things up rather a lot and also sets the story in the mid-1930s (as are all the Suchet Poirot films).]<br /><br />1924 04	While the Light Lasts <br />		— lost loves, and found, on safari in Africa; moody<br /><br />1925 10	Within a Wall <br />		— artistic integrity and Great Love, several kinds; sentimental<br />			but with a definitely sharp edge<br /><br />1926 01	House of Dreams <br />		— extremely sweet - but odd - tale of love, money, and illness<br /><br />1926 07	The Lonely God <br />		— unusual and very sweet little story of love found, then lost, <br />			then found again, with an entirely improbable ending<br /><br />1927 02	The Edge <br />		— the pain (and the temptations) of unrequited love; excellent<br />			psychological touches and good writing but a sappy ending<br /><br />1930 05	Manx Gold <br />		— peculiar treasure hunt tale worked up only as a promotional <br />			package for tourism on the Isle of Man; style very confusing<br />			now although it might have been fun at the time. <br /><br />1932 01	The Mystery of the Spanish Chest <br />		— beautifully classic whodunit case for Poirot, novella length, <br />			of love gone bad and a fatally beautiful woman; <br />			rewritten &amp; pub'd as Mystery of the Baghdad Chest, 1960<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7124548830851757353" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


