<div id="review_3173024012" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3173024012" />
    <a title="Kate" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/84373319-kate"><img alt="Kate" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1539707419p2/84373319.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3173024012?book_show_action=true">Feb 02, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kate" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kate" href="/user/show/84373319-kate">Kate</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3173024012" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11982257806153409962">Enjoyable collection of Agatha Christie&apos;s early short stories. I always forget the supernatural quality her stories possess, whether it&apos;s overt (House of Dreams/The Lonely God) or merely Christie&apos;s omnipresent, subtle and uncanny perception of the human condition.<br/><br/>I enjoyed the &apos;Afterword&apos; at the end of each tale, which explains publication details or events in Agatha Christie&apos;s life she might have drawn inspiration from. These snippets intrigued me enough to want to read a biography of her life </span>
  <span id="freeText11982257806153409962" style="display:none">Enjoyable collection of Agatha Christie's early short stories. I always forget the supernatural quality her stories possess, whether it's overt (House of Dreams/The Lonely God) or merely Christie's omnipresent, subtle and uncanny perception of the human condition.<br /><br />I enjoyed the 'Afterword' at the end of each tale, which explains publication details or events in Agatha Christie's life she might have drawn inspiration from. These snippets intrigued me enough to want to read a biography of her life so I can learn more about her.<br /><br />For early work the level of craft and style is awing. Addictive reading, devoured over two afternoons!</span>
  <a data-text-id="11982257806153409962" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


